[1]
Date: Mon 8 Sep 2014
Source: Calgary Sun [edited]
http://www.calgarysun.com/2014/09/08/recall-of-pork-products-in-calgary-and-edmonton-expands-after-e-coli-outbreak


The recall of raw pork products due to possible _E. coli_ [O157] contamination has been expanded to more stores in Calgary and Edmonton.

Raw pork products bought at Trimming Fresh Meat (6219 Centre St NW) between 15 and 22 Jul 2014 and products from Hiep Hoa Asian Food (4710 17 Ave SE) between 15 and 29 Jul 2014 should be thrown out or returned to the store where they were purchased.

According to the Canadian Food Inspection Agency website, the products may not look or smell spoiled, however they still have the potential to make consumers sick. The expanded recall also includes frozen pork spring rolls, pork buns, and pork wontons from Vihn Fat Food Products (10630 97 St) in Edmonton sold between 10 Jul 2014 and 5 Sep 2014, which should be thrown out or returned to the point of purchase.

Alberta Health Services [AHS] said 153 people were diagnosed with _E. coli_ [O157] between 10 Jul 2014 and 3 Sep 2014, with 19 having to be hospitalized and 5 of those suffering the most serious form of the disease, which affects the kidneys [hemolytic uremic syndrome]. AHS officials said 45 people were hospitalized in Calgary and 46 in Edmonton and the remainder at smaller centres around the province.

Steps can be taken to avoid foodborne illnesses, including washing your hands thoroughly using hot, soapy water -- especially after using the washroom or changing a diaper -- cooking pork and beef products to at least 71 deg C (160 deg F) and thoroughly washing any cooking utensils that touch raw meat.

[Byline: Dave Dormer]

