[The DNA "fingerprinting" is awaited to confirm the association between the pork and the human cases. As with ground beef, adequate cooking and appropriate kitchen hygiene will have diminished the risk. Whether the pork was contaminated with beef or was the primary cause of contamination is not at this point clear.

Pigs are uncommon reservoirs for enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ cases in humans. - Mod.LL

Maps of Canada can be seen at http://ftp2.cits.rncan.gc.ca/pub/geott/atlas_tif/atlas6/Reference/English/can_eng.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2759887,263. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
